   Oh yeah, thanks Dante, the BC is great.
   [91]8
   Michael Dolan
   September 15, 2013
   Great place to see music.
   Great place to play music.
   Thanks for the backstory.
   [92]9
   Mike Fekula
   September 17, 2013
   OK, so this was a great article and a trip down memory lane. Too bad
   that some people cannot speak positively about the Black Cat without
   trashing other venues. After our beloved DC Punk Demi-God Ian Mackaye,
   the One who cannot be contradicted, has to "inform" us about all the
   supposed limitations of the 930 Club - all of which never stopped him
   from playing there - we then get the remarks from little brother Alec
   Mackaye, who gratuitously bashes The Bayou: "which was a hideous,
   shithole bar..."
   Well, I guess it is sacrilege in DC to contradict the Mackaye family
   but let's just say that some of us have appreciated all of the 930
   Club's formatting, with or without the punk demi-gods; and we
   definitely remember the Bayou differently. I saw my share of punk shows
   at the Bayou including the Ramones, 999, and Stiff Little Fingers, and
   completely enjoyed the experience. The Bayou had a fairly diverse
   format which I assume probably did not include the DC punks so perhaps
   this is about settling old scores. I guess some of the punks couldn't
   handle a venue that had the Skip Castro Band with any frequency. In any
   case, there has always been a number of good clubs in the DC area and
   as the article pointed out, a lot of them didn't last, but it wasn't
   for lack of effort. Kudos to Dante Ferrando and the Black Cat for
   putting the music out there for the people and earning the community
   support that has allowed them to keep going all these years.

